WEBVTT

1
00:00:11.460 --> 00:00:15.360
Every day, a sea of decisions stretches before us. Some

2
00:00:15.380 --> 00:00:18.460
are small and unimportant, but others have a larger impact

3
00:00:18.500 --> 00:00:21.670
on our lives. For example, which politician should I vote

4
00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:25.220
for? Should I try the latest diet craze? Or will

5
00:00:25.300 --> 00:00:29.580
email make me a millionaire? We're bombarded with so many

6
00:00:29.660 --> 00:00:32.809
decisions that it's impossible to make a perfect choice every

7
00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:36.550
time. But there are many ways to improve our chances,

8
00:00:36.960 --> 00:00:41.110
and one particularly effective technique is critical thinking. This is

9
00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:43.560
a way of approaching a question that allows us to

10
00:00:43.620 --> 00:00:47.670
carefully deconstruct a situation, reveal its hidden issues, such as

11
00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.100
bias and manipulation, and make the best decision. If the

12
00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:55.460
critical part sounds negative, that's because in a way it

13
00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:58.730
is. Rather than choosing an answer because it feels right,

14
00:00:59.089 --> 00:01:03.000
a person who uses critical thinking subjects all available options

15
00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:06.840
to scrutiny and skepticism. Using the tools at their disposal,

16
00:01:07.100 --> 00:01:11.220
they'll eliminate everything but the most useful and reliable information.

17
00:01:12.560 --> 00:01:15.480
There are many different ways of approaching critical thinking, but

18
00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:19.180
here's one five-step process that may help you solve any

19
00:01:19.250 --> 00:01:24.210
number of problems. One, formulate your question. In other

20
00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:27.420
words, know what you're looking for. This isn't always as

21
00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.260
straightforward as it sounds. For example, if you're deciding whether

22
00:01:31.300 --> 00:01:34.220
to try out the newest diet craze, your reasons for

23
00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:37.899
doing so may be obscured by other factors, like claims

24
00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:41.340
that you'll see results in just two weeks. But if

25
00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.350
you approach the situation with a clear view of what

26
00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:47.980
you're actually trying to accomplish by dieting, whether that's weight

27
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.960
loss, better nutrition, or having more energy, that'll equip you

28
00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:55.640
to sift through this information critically, find what you're looking

29
00:01:55.680 --> 00:01:58.920
for, and decide whether the new fad really suits your

30
00:01:58.960 --> 00:02:03.200
needs. Two, gather your information.

31
00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:06.100
There's lots of it out there, so having a clear

32
00:02:06.200 --> 00:02:09.080
idea of your question will help you determine what's relevant.

33
00:02:09.560 --> 00:02:11.580
If you're trying to decide on a diet to improve

34
00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:14.700
your nutrition, you may ask an expert for their advice

35
00:02:14.780 --> 00:02:18.780
or seek other people's testimonies. Information gathering helps you weigh

36
00:02:18.820 --> 00:02:21.890
different options, moving you closer to a decision that meets

37
00:02:21.920 --> 00:02:26.900
your goal. Three, apply the information, something you do

38
00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:31.549
by asking critical questions. Facing a decision, ask yourself, "What

39
00:02:31.660 --> 00:02:35.910
concepts are at work? What assumptions exist? Is my interpretation

40
00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:40.260
of the information logically sound?" For example, in an email

41
00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:44.300
that promises you millions, you should consider, "What is shaping

42
00:02:44.340 --> 00:02:47.340
my approach to this situation? Do I assume the sender

43
00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:50.240
is telling the truth? Based on the evidence, is it

44
00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:54.760
logical to assume I'll win any money?" Four,

45
00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:59.500
consider the implications. Imagine it's election time and you've selected

46
00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:02.280
a political candidate based on their promise to make it

47
00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:05.329
cheaper for drivers to fill up on gas. At first

48
00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:09.040
glance, that seems great, but what about the long-term environmental

49
00:03:09.080 --> 00:03:13.190
effects? If gasoline use is less restricted by cost, this

50
00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:16.620
could also cause a huge surge in air pollution, an

51
00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:21.320
unintended consequence that's important to think about. Five,

52
00:03:21.820 --> 00:03:25.530
explore other points of view. Ask yourself why so many

53
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:28.810
people are drawn to the policies of the opposing political

54
00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:32.580
candidate. Even if you disagree with everything that candidate says,

55
00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:36.600
exploring the full spectrum of viewpoints might explain why some

56
00:03:36.640 --> 00:03:39.870
policies that don't seem valid to you appeal to others.

57
00:03:40.920 --> 00:03:44.160
This will allow you to explore alternatives, evaluate your own

58
00:03:44.200 --> 00:03:47.880
choices, and ultimately help you make more informed decisions.

59
00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:52.640
This five-step process is just one tool, and it certainly

60
00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:56.640
won't eradicate difficult decisions from our lives, but it can

61
00:03:56.680 --> 00:03:59.680
help us increase the number of positive choices we make.

62
00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:03.080
Critical thinking can give us the tools to sift through

63
00:04:03.090 --> 00:04:06.280
a sea of information and find what we're looking for.

64
00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:08.480
And if enough of us use it, it has the

65
00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:11.840
power to make the world a more reasonable place.
